Comparing Social Networks in Archaeology

ASM 591 Final Project Proposal

Robert Bischoff

10/22/2019

Project Background: My Dissertation Topic

  • My dissertation research focuses on small arrow points in the United States Southwest during two time periods:
    • The AD 800s was a period of rapid community growth and reorganization
    • Similarly, the post-AD 1350 period was also a period of major community reorganization
  • Changes in social networks for both time periods have been studied through the use of ceramic assemblages

Project Background: My Dissertation Topic

  • My research expands this analysis to study these social networks through projectile points and other available data, including ceramics
  • The goal of this class project is to create a general model to compare social networks created through different social processes
    • These processes are the production and circulation of ceramics and projectile points

Social Networks in Archaeology

  • Social networks analysis is becoming a common tool in archaeology
  • Most analyses consider networks created from one type of artifact–usually ceramics
    • Note: these social networks do not necessarily reflect actual social connections in the past–a good definition is that they represent the potential for interaction
  • An example of this is the Southwest Social Networks Project (e.g., Mills et al. 2013)
    • although in some analyses the authors also considered obsidian exchange

Southwest Social Networks Project

Social Networks in Archaeology

  • A number of studies have used agent-based models to examine social networks (e.g., Brughmans and Poblome 2016; Graham 2006; Gravel-Miguel 2017; Gravel-Miguel and Wren 2018)
    • Claudine is currently working on closely related concepts to my question
    • My question is more specific to ceramics and projectile points in settled, agricultural societies

My Model

  • Main question
    • How do social networks differ between ceramics and projectile points?

My Model

  • Background questions
    • What processes affect ceramic and projectile point circulation?
      • Projectile point exchange is less common–hunters make their own points
      • Only some agents produce pottery–but everyone needs it
      • Ethnographic data suggests gender affects processes
  • What processes affect discard and the creation of site assemblages?
    • Ceramics and Projectile Points are discarded differently, likely in different places

Possible Extensions

  • Add permanent relocation to other villages
  • Add distance effects–less likely to hunt or visit if farther away
  • Create social networks that affect interaction and exchange
  • Change odds of discard to match activity (e.g., more likely to lose points while hunting, more likely to drop a pot at home)
  • Add cultural transmission

Output

  • Each village will have an assemblage consisting of all ceramics and projectile points deposited there
  • These data can be either exported and analyzed in R or analyzed within Netlogo to create similarity networks and network statistics
